ENTSOE DATA Exploration & prediction¶

This notebook is focused on exploration of avalible ENTSOE data and use gathered knowledge to build a classificator.

The most important features for our classifier will be ENTSOE production estimations of solar and wind energy and of course, the open price, which is the first satisfied order of the day. With various possible features, first we are going to aggregate some of them and select the most appropriate.

In [6]:
data.iloc[:,19:-16].hist(bins=25,figsize=(18,10))
plt.show()

Our target is to predict whether the settlement_0 price is greater than open_0 price or not. Due to NaN values in dataset, we have to handle them carefuly to mantain as many instances as possible.

The data split ratio is 7:1 and the following methods will be used:

  • Logistic Regression
  • Support Vector Machines
  • Nearest Neighbor
  • XGBoost
  • MLP

Now it is right time to handle suspicious values. In this case, we want to omit instances with negative mean price value, which could drasticly influence our classifier. Negative mean price values are usually caused by unexpected events, in our dataset mainly by the coronavirus pandemic.

Model¶

In the following part, we are going to train a validate several models. In this case, we are using a custom score function, which is based on profit and loss. For every instance, our model predicts increase or decrease of open price and in accordance with this, we would hypothetically place 1kWh order on the bid or ask side. Every time the model predicts correctly, we would eventually earn the difference between open and settlement price, or we would lose it in opposite case. The output of this custom scorer will be a sum of these profits and losses relative to one instance.

As we can see below, the top 20 price differences are quite significant. If we consider, that our test set is only around 45 instances, those with great price difference could have serious influence on the output of profit and loss scorer.

In [53]:
def create_df(Xlog,Xnn,Xgb,SV):
    keys = {"X_log": Xlog[:,0], "X_nn": Xnn[:,0], "X_xgb": Xgb[:,0], "SVC": SV}
    c = pd.DataFrame(keys)
    return c

def join_df(X1,X2):
    X2.index = X1.index
    X = X1.join(X2)
    return X

Xc_test = join_df(X_test,c_test)

In [63]:
def neural_settings(X_train,y_train,mlp_clas,svm_clas_opt,xgb_clas,nn_clas_opt,log_clas_opt,X):

    skfolds = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=7, shuffle = True, random_state = 420)
    pl_vec = []
    acc_vec = []
    pl_vec_train = []
    acc_vec_train = []
    X_set = X_train.copy()
    y_set = y_train.copy()

    for train_index, test_index in skfolds.split(X_set, y_set):
        clone_clf = clone(mlp_clas)
        svm_clone = clone(svm_clas_opt)
        xgb_clone = clone(xgb_clas)
        nn_clone = clone(nn_clas_opt)
        log_clone = clone(log_clas_opt)

        X_train_folds = X_set.iloc[train_index]
        y_train_folds = y_set.iloc[train_index]
        X_test_fold = X_set.iloc[test_index]
        y_test_fold = y_set.iloc[test_index]

        svm_clone.fit(X_train_folds,y_train_folds)
        xgb_clone.fit(X_train_folds,y_train_folds)
        nn_clone.fit(X_train_folds,y_train_folds)
        log_clone.fit(X_train_folds,y_train_folds)

        SVC_dec_train = svm_clone.decision_function(X_train_folds)
        SVC_dec_test = svm_clone.decision_function(X_test_fold)
        log_prob_train = log_clone.predict_proba(X_train_folds)
        log_prob_test = log_clone.predict_proba(X_test_fold)
        nn_prob_train = nn_clone.predict_proba(X_train_folds)
        nn_prob_test = nn_clone.predict_proba(X_test_fold)
        xgb_prob_train = xgb_clone.predict_proba(X_train_folds)
        xgb_prob_test = xgb_clone.predict_proba(X_test_fold)

        c_train_folds = create_df(log_prob_train,nn_prob_train,xgb_prob_train,SVC_dec_train)
        c_test_fold = create_df(log_prob_test,nn_prob_test,xgb_prob_test,SVC_dec_test)

        clone_clf.fit(c_train_folds, y_train_folds)
        y_pred = clone_clf.predict(c_test_fold)
        pl = PLmetrics(y_test_fold, y_pred, X)
        pl_vec.append(pl)
        acc = metrics.accuracy_score(y_test_fold,y_pred)
        acc_vec.append(acc)
        y_pred_train = clone_clf.predict(c_train_folds)
        pl_tr = PLmetrics(y_train_folds, y_pred_train, X)
        pl_vec_train.append(pl_tr)
        acc_train = metrics.accuracy_score(y_train_folds,y_pred_train)
        acc_vec_train.append(acc_train)
    return pl_vec, pl_vec_train, acc_vec, acc_vec_train

Summary¶

To sum up, predictions provided by individual models are not convincing at all. We used classifiers with different basis and then we used their predictions as an input for neural network (MLP classifier). In the following figure, we show cross validation results on train set for all individual classifier and the neural network as well. In addition, there is a highlighted point representing results on test set for each.

Furthemore, in the following table we compare classification results on the test set in table. As we mentioned before, the test set is quite small and extreme price differences can cause large deviations in p&l results. During this research, we found out that different train-test splits can provide diverse results.
